e many consider wartime imprisonment an isolated historical moment, Inouye shows how imprisonment and the suspension of rights have continued to impact political discourse and public policies in both the United States and Canada long after their supposed political and legal reversal. In particular, she attends to how activist groups can use the persistence of memory to engage empathetically with people across often profound cultural and political divides. This book addresses the mechanisms by which injustice can transform both its victims and its perpetrators, detailing the dangers of suspending rights during times of crisis as well as the opportunities for more empathetic agency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aCollective memoryxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aCollective memoryzUnited States. 0aJapanese AmericansxEvacuation and relocation, 1942-1945. 0aJapanese AmericansxPolitical activityxHistory. 0aPolitical prisonersxEffect of imprisonment onxUnited States. 0aPolitical prisonersxEffect of imprisonment onzUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration campsxUnited States. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xConcentration campszUnited States. 4aExecutive Order 9066. 4aJapanese Americans. 4aJapanese Canadians. 4aNikkei North Americans. 4acivil liberties. 4aempathetic agency. 4aincarceration. 4amemory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781503600560zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503600560423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503600560.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles